One over-long line holds a nested literal, but breaking the OUTER literal alone
brings the inner under the 80-column budget — so the inner is left inline. This
is the case that tells outermost-first apart from innermost-first: an
innermost-first implementation would explode the inner literal too, because it
never re-measures after the outer break decides the inner no longer needs it.
goast.Inspect visits the outer literal first and breakFirstWideLiteral stops at
the first match per round, so only the outer breaks here.

-- input.gsx --
package ui

var rows = []Row{{alpha: "aaaaaaaaaaaaaaa", beta: "bbbbbbbbbbbbbbb", gamma: "ccccccccccccccc"}}
-- fmt.golden --
package ui

var rows = []Row{
	{alpha: "aaaaaaaaaaaaaaa", beta: "bbbbbbbbbbbbbbb", gamma: "ccccccccccccccc"},
}
